UNDIAGNOSED REACTION - INDIA: (MADHYA PRADESH) AMPICILLIN, PREGNANT PATIENTS, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*****************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 30 Oct 2017 6:08 PM IST
Source: News18 [edited]
http://www.news18.com/news/india/50-pregnant-women-fall-ill-after-being-given-antibiotic-injections-at-mp-hospital-2-critical-1561725.html


As many as 50 pregnant women have been reported unwell at Kamla Raja Hospital in Gwalior [Madhya Pradesh] after being administered with antibiotic injections. The incident, which happened late on [Sun 29 Oct 2017], has left 2 patients extremely critical. 5 such patients were also shifted to the ICU after their condition deteriorated.

At around 9 pm on Sunday, the pregnant patients of 2 wards in Gynaecology Department were given ampicillin injections. Very soon, the women started complaining of shivering and their families reported the matter to the duty staff, which immediately brought it to the notice of the senior doctors. Police and security guards were called in by the hospital staff to avoid any untoward incident and protests from the families of the patients. Soon, assistant superintendent Dr Rita Mishra, HoD [Head of Department] Dr Yashodhara Gaur, and others reached the spot. The physicians had a tough time persuading the families to let them continue with the treatment.

5 of these patients were soon shifted to the ICU after their condition deteriorated drastically. Speaking to CNN-News18, Dr Sanjay Chandel, acting superintendent of the hospital, claimed that women patients complained of feeling cold after being given ampicillin injections, which had been kept as samples for inquiry. "5 women were shifted to ICU. 3 of them are stable, but the condition of the other 2 is serious," Dr Chandel said.

Dr Rita Mishra said it was difficult to immediately ascertain what led to the reaction -- the injection or distilled water. As a precautionary measure, the staff has been asked not to administer ampicillin injections for the time being, she added.

[Byline: Vivek Trivedi]

