Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Ampicillin is a penicillin-like antibiotic that can be used orally, intramuscularly or intravenously to treat bacterial infections; ampicillin is also used to prevent infections, such as group B streptococcal infection in mothers and newborns (given during labor, 2 g of ampicillin intravenously initially, then 1 g intravenously every 4 hours until delivery, which may be why the drug was being administered to some of these pregnant women (https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/rr5111a1.htm).

The incident described above involves as many as 50 pregnant hospitalized women who received ampicillin injections. Soon thereafter the women developed a shivering reaction, severe enough to require ICU admissions for 5 patients; the condition of 3 of the 5 ICU admissions is stable, but the condition of the other 2 is critical. It is not stated whether the injections were IV or IM, or if the patients were febrile or developed shock, or the time-line of this event -- that is, if all the pregnant patients were given ampicillin at the same time, if they were all given the same lot of ampicillin, if others were given ampicillin, but were unaffected, and for what reason they were given ampicillin. More information on this outbreak would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources.

A febrile reaction to ampicillin itself could occur due to allergy, but 50 patients having a febrile allergic reaction within a short time of each other is unlikely. More likely the patients are reacting to a contaminant in the antibiotic solution itself or contamination of some ancillary fluid used to administered the antibiotic.

Endotoxin, also known as bacterial pyrogen (fever-inducing agent), is one of the most potent bacterial toxins. The only source of endotoxin is gram-negative bacteria, where it comprises about 75 percent of the bacterial cell wall. In minute quantities endotoxin can cause shaking chills, followed by fever, tachycardia, respiratory distress, and hypotension; larger amounts can lead to irreversible shock and death. The release of endotoxin from Gram-negative bacteria can take place after death and lysis of the bacterial cell. So cultures may be negative for the Gram-negative organism. In addition, a pyrogenic reaction can also be produced by some Gram-positive bacteria, mycobacteria, fungi, and viruses.

ProMED-mail has posted previously on outbreaks due to Gram-negative bacterial contaminated IV preparations. _Enterobacter_ species was the cause of the massive multi-institutional outbreak of sepsis related to contaminated IV fluids in the late 1970's (1) and was the cause of an outbreak in neonates due to contaminated IV fluids (2).

References
----------
1. Maki DG, Rhame FS, Mackel DC, Bennett JV: Nationwide epidemic of septicemia caused by contaminated intravenous products: I. Epidemiologic and clinical features. Am J Med 1976; 60(4): 471-85; abstract available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1274981.
2. Matsaniotis NS, Syriopoulou VPh, Theodoridou MC, et al: Enterobacter sepsis in infants and children due to contaminated intravenous fluids. Infection Control 1984; 5(10): 471-7; abstract available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6567611.

Maps of India can be seen at http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5419820,2251.
Gwalior, with a population of about 1 million residents, is a city in central India in the state of Madhya Pradesh, located 319 km (198 mi) south of Delhi, the capital city of India. Its location can be seen on the map at https://www.google.co.uk/maps/place/Gwalior,+Madhya+Pradesh,+India. - Mod.ML]
